{"parse":{"title":"sea","pageid":24568,"redirects":[],"wikitext":"{{also|Appendix:Variations of \"sea\"}}\n==Translingual==\n\n===Etymology===\nMost likely an {{abbrev|mul|nocap=1|en:'''Se'''m'''a'''i}}.\n\n===Symbol===\n{{mul-symbol}}\n\n# {{ISO 639|3}}\n\n===See also===\n* {{langcat}}\n\n==English==\n[[Image:Nordsee Wellen.JPG|thumb|The sea.]]\n\n===Etymology===\n{{inh+|en|enm|see}}, from {{inh|en|ang|sǣ}}, from {{inh|en|gmw-pro|*saiwi||body of water}}, from {{inh|en|gem-pro|*saiwiz}}, itself either:\n* {{der+|en|ine-pro|*sh₂ey-|*sh₂ey-wo-|to be fierce, afflict}}.<ref>{{R:gem:HGE|*saiwiz|314}}</ref> Related to {{cog|la|saevus||wild, fierce}}, {{cog|txb|saiwe||itch}}{{,}} and {{cog|lv|sievs}}, {{m|lv|sīvs||sharp, biting}}. More at {{m|en|sore}}.\n* {{der+|en|gem-pro|*sīhwaną||to percolate, filter}},<ref>{{R:gem:EDPG|*saiwi-|423}}</ref> from {{der|en|ine-pro|*seykʷ-}}.<ref>{{R:gem:EDPG|*sīhwan-|435–436}}</ref>\n{{col-top|2|cog}}\nCognate with {{cog|yol|zea}}, {{m|yol|zee|t=sea}}, {{cog|frr|See}}, {{m|frr|sia}}, {{m|frr|siie|t=sea; lake}}, {{cog|stq|See}}, {{m|stq|Säi|t=sea}}, {{cog|fy|see|t=sea}}, {{cog|cim,mhn|sea|t=lake}}, {{cog|nl|zee|t=sea}}, {{cog|de,nds-de|See|t=sea}}, {{cog|li|Sië}}, {{m|li|zieë|t=sea, ocean; lake}}, {{cog|lb|Séi|t=lake}}, {{cog|vls|zji|t=sea; seaside}}, {{cog|da|sø|t=sea; lake}}, {{cog|fo|sjógvur|t=sea; big wave}}, {{cog|is|sjár}}, {{m|is|sjór}}, {{m|is|sær|t=sea}}, {{cog|nb,nn|sjø|t=sea, ocean; lake}}, {{cog|sv|sjö|t=sea; lake; big wave}}, {{cog|got|𐍃𐌰𐌹𐍅𐍃|t=lake, sea; marshland}}.\n{{col-bottom}}\n\n===Pronunciation===\n* {{enPR|sē}}, {{IPA|en|/siː/}}\n* {{audio|en|En-uk-sea.ogg|a=UK}}\n* {{audio|en|LL-Q1860 (eng)-Naomi Persephone Amethyst (NaomiAmethyst)-sea.wav|a=GA}}\n* {{audio|en|LL-Q1860 (eng)-Back ache-sea.wav}}\n* {{audio|en|en-us-sea.ogg|a=US}}\n* {{enPR|sā|a=obsolete}}, {{IPA|en|/seɪ/}}\n* {{homophones|en|C|cee|see}}\n* {{rhymes|en|iː|s=1}}\n\n===Noun===\n{{en-noun}}\n\n# {{senseid|en|Q165}}A [[large]] [[body]] of [[salt water]].\n#: {{syn|en|ogin|q=UK, nautical and navy|[[briny]] (literary, U.K.)}}\n#* {{quote-book|en|year=1780|author=w:William Cowper|title=Twenty-ſix Letters on Religious Subjects{{...}} To which are added Hymns{{...}}|edition=4th|chapter={{w|God Moves in a Mysterious Way|Light Shining out of Darkneſs}}|url=https://books.google.co.nz/books?id=rKhVAAAAcAAJ|page=252|text={{smallcaps|God}} moves in a myſterious way, / His wonders to perform; / He plants his footſteps in the '''ſea''', / And rides upon the ſtorm.}}\n## The [[ocean]]; the [[continuous]] body of salt water covering a [[majority]] of the [[Earth]]'s [[surface]].\n##* {{RQ:KJV|Leviticus|11|9|sig=&#91;K5&#93;|page=194|column=2|passage=These ſhal ye eat, of all that are in the waters: whatſoeuer hath finnes and ſcales in the waters, in the '''ſeas''', and in the riuers, them ſhall ye eate.}}\n##* {{quote-book|en|year=1719|author=Nicholas Rowe|title=Lucan's Pharsalia: Translated into English Verse|location=Dublin|publisher=James Carson|chapter=Book V|page=183|pageurl=https://books.google.com/books?id=IjhWAAAAcAAJ&pg=PA183|passage=At length the universal Wreck appear'd,/ To Cæsar's self, ev'n worthy to be fear'd./ Why all these Pains, this Toil of Fate (he cries)/ This Labour of the '''Seas''', and Earth, and Skies?/ All Nature, and the Gods at once alarm'd,/ Against my little Boat and me are arm'd.}}\n##* {{quote-book|en|year=1833|author=William Hazlitt|chapter=Notes of a Journey Through France and Italy|title=Greenbank's Periodical Library|volume=I|section=chapter 1|page=173|pageurl=https://books.google.com/books?id=LXZIAQAAIAAJ&pg=PA173|passage=There is something in being near the '''sea''', like the confines of eternity. It is a new element, a pure abstraction. The mind loves to hover on that which is endless, and forever the same. People wonder at a steam-boat, the invention of man, managed by man, that makes its liquid path like an iron railway through the '''sea'''—I wonder at the '''sea''' itself, that vast Leviathan, rolled round the earth, smiling in its sleep, waked into fury, fathomless, boundless, a huge world of water-drops.—Whence is it, whither goes it, is it of eternity, or of nothing?}}\n##* {{quote-journal|en|year=1922|month=March|author=J. S. Fletcher|title=The Mystery of Ravensdene Court|journal=Everybody's Magazine|volume=XLVI|issue=3|page=162|pageurl=https://books.google.com/books?id=6XJIAAAAYAAJ&pg=RA2-PA162|passage=As we stood there watching, the long yellow light on the eastern horizon suddenly changed in color—first to a roseate flush, then to a warm crimson; the scenes round us, sky, '''sea''', and land, brightened as if by magic.}}\n## A body of salt water smaller than an ocean, generally forming part of, or connecting with, an ocean or a larger sea.\n##: {{ux|en|The Mediterranean '''Sea''', the Caribbean '''Sea''', the '''Sea''' of Crete, etc.}}\n# A [[lake]], especially if large or if [[salty]] or [[brackish]].\n#: {{ux|en|The Caspian '''Sea''', the '''Sea''' of Galilee, the Salton '''Sea''', etc.}}\n# A single [[wave]]; [[billow]].\n#* {{RQ:Bligh Voyage|chapter=II|page=14|passage=One '''ſea''' broke away the ſpare yards and ſpars out of the ſtarboard main chains. Another heavy '''ſea''' broke into the ſhip and ſtove all the boats. Several caſks of beer, that had been laſhed upon deck, were broke looſe and waſhed overboard, and it was not without great difficulty and riſk that we were able to ſecure the boats from being waſhed away entirely.}}\n#* {{RQ:Asbjornsen Braekstad Tales|chapter=Mackerel Trolling|page=187|passage='If they buy three cords of birch logs,' said the witch, 'but they must be exact measure—and no bargaining about the price, and if they throw overboard the one cord of logs, piece by piece, when the first '''sea''' comes, and the other cord, piece by piece, when the second '''sea''' comes, and the third cord, piece by piece, when the third '''sea''' comes, then it's all over with us.'}}\n# The [[swell]] of the sea, especially when high or rough.\n#* {{quote-book|en|year=1913|author={{w|Edgar Rice Burroughs}}|title={{w|The Return of Tarzan}}|publisher=Ballantine Books|location=New York|year_published=1963|page=150|passage=“Where can they be?” he cried. “They cannot have gone down, for there has been no '''sea''', and they were afloat after the yacht sank—I saw them all.”}}\n#* {{quote-book|en|year=1952|author=Ernest Hemingway|title=The Old Man and the Sea|passage=There was a small '''sea''' rising with the wind coming up from the east and at noon the old man's left hand was uncramped.}}\n#* '''2020''' June 8, National Weather Service Boston, 2:38 PM EDT marine forecast\n#*: High pressure will maintain light winds and flat '''seas''' through Tue night. ... Potential for briefly choppy 3 ft '''seas''' near South Coast...\n# {{lb|en|attributive|in combination}} Living or used in or on the sea; of, near, or like the sea.\n#: {{ux|en|'''Sea'''man, '''sea''' gauge, '''sea''' monster, '''sea''' horse, '''sea''' level, '''sea'''worthy, '''sea'''port, '''sea'''board, etc.}}\n# {{lb|en|figurative}} Anything resembling the [[vastness]] or [[turbulence]] of the sea in mass, size or quantity.\n#* {{RQ:Shakespeare Hamlet Q1-2|version=Q2|act=III|scene=i|sig=G2|page=54|passage={{w|To be, or not to be}}, that is the queſtion, / Whether tis nobler in the minde to ſuffer / The ſlings and arrowes of outragious fortune, / Or to take Armes againſt a '''ſea''' of troubles, / And by oppoſing, end them, to die to ſleepe / No more, and by a ſleepe, to ſay we end / The hart-ake, and the thouſand naturall ſhocks / That fleſh is heire to; {{...}}}}\n#* {{quote-book|en|year=1980|title=Slaves on Horseback: The Evolution of the Islamic Polity|author=[[w:Patricia Crone|Patria Crone]]|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=0 521 52940 9|text=Secondly, in terms of geopolitics Central Asia was a huge '''sea''' of barbarians set in the midst of interlocking continents. Thanks to its border on the Siberian forest in the north, it was open to barbarian incomers who would upset existing polities and set migrations going.}}\n#* {{quote-book|en|year=1980|title=AA Book of British Villages|publisher=Drive Publications Ltd|page=102|text=The beck is crossed by a pretty ford and a number of bridges, and in spring the cottages look out over a dancing '''sea''' of daffodils.}}\n#* {{quote-journal|en|date=April 9, 2013|author=Andrei Lankov|title=Stay Cool. Call North Korea’s Bluff.|work=New York Times|url=http://www.nytimes.com/2013/04/10/opinion/stay-cool-call-north-koreas-bluff.html?_r=0\n|passage=In the last two decades, North Korea has on various occasions conducted highly provocative missile and nuclear tests and promised to turn Seoul into a '''sea''' of fire.}}\n#* {{quote-web|en|site=w:Instagram|author=@thefunerallife|date=11 May 2026|text=When the newbie is struggling to find the femoral in a '''sea''' of fat tissue so you teach them the power of perseverance}}\n# {{lb|en|physics}} A [[constant]] [[flux]] of [[gluon]]s splitting into [[quark]]s, which [[annihilate]] to produce further gluons.\n# {{lb|en|planetology}} A large, [[dark]] [[plain#Etymology 3|plain]] of [[rock]]; a [[mare#Etymology 3|mare]].\n#: {{ux|en|The Apollo 11 mission landed in the '''Sea''' of Tranquility.}}\n# {{lb|en|planetology}} A very large lake of [[liquid]] [[hydrocarbon]].\n\n====Derived terms====\n\n=====Proper nouns=====\n{{col4|en|title=Names of seas\n|Adriatic Sea|Argentine Sea\n|Aegean Sea\n|Baltic Sea\n|Barents Sea|Beaufort Sea\n|Bering Sea\n|Black Sea\n|Camotes Sea|Caribbean Sea\n|Caspian Sea\n|Celtic Sea\n|Coral Sea\n|Dead Sea\n|East Sea\n|German Sea\n|Greenland Sea||Hinder Sea|Sea of the Philistines|The Sea\n|Imarpik Sea\n|Inland Sea\n|Ionian Sea\n|Irish Sea\n|Java Sea\n|Kara Sea\n|Labrador Sea|Myrtoan Sea|Ligurian Sea\n|Mediterranean Sea\n|North Sea\n|Norwegian Sea\n|Philippine Sea\n|Red Sea\n|Ross Sea\n|Salt Sea|Sea Lake\n|Sea of Azov\n|Sea of Galilee\n|Sea of Japan|Tappan Sea\n|Sea of Marmara\n|Sea of Okhotsk\n|Sea of Sodom\n|Sea of the Hebrides\n|South China Sea\n|Tasman Sea\n|Timor Sea|Scotia Sea|Solomon Sea\n|Tyrrhenian Sea\n|Wadden Sea\n|Weddell Sea|Banda Sea|Seto Inland Sea|Sulu Sea\n}}\n\n{{col4|en|title=Places, other than actual seas, with \"sea\" in their title\n|Allhallows-on-Sea\n|Bexhill-on-Sea\n|Birchington-on-Sea|Mundesley-on-Sea\n|Burnham-on-Sea\n|Caister-on-Sea\n|Cardiff-by-the-Sea\n|Carmel-by-the-Sea\n|Chelsea-on-Sea\n|Clacton-on-Sea\n|Cley next the Sea\n|Frinton-on-Sea\n|Goring-by-Sea\n|Gorleston-on-Sea\n|Greatstone-on-Sea\n|Holland-on-Sea\n|Hopton-on-Sea\n|Kingston by Sea\n|Knott End-on-Sea\n|Leigh-on-Sea\n|Leysdown-on-Sea\n|Littlestone-on-Sea\n|Lydd-on-Sea\n|Marske-by-the-Sea\n|Middleton-on-Sea\n|Milford-on-Sea\n|Minster-on-Sea\n|Newbiggin-by-the-Sea\n|Newton-by-the-Sea\n|Red Sea Hills\n|Rhos-on-Sea\n|Saltburn-by-the-Sea\n|Seabreeze\n|Seaford\n|Sealand\n|Sea Mills\n|Sea Point\n|Seatown\n|Seaview\n|Shoreham-by-Sea\n|Southend-on-Sea\n|St Anne's on the Sea\n|St Leonards-on-Sea\n|Sutton on Sea\n|Wells-next-the-Sea\n|Westcliff-on-Sea\n|Westgate-on-Sea\n}}\n\n=====Common nouns=====\n{{col4|en|title=Terms derived from ''sea'' (species)\n|Cortez sea chub\n|deep-sea prawn\n|green sea turtle\n|hawksbill sea turtle\n|Japanese sea lion|sea arch|sea control ship|sea dahlia|sea oxeye daisy|sea pangolin|sea sheller|sea shelling|sea sorrel|sea-marigold\n|Japanese sea perch\n|Kemp's ridley sea turtle\n|loggerhead sea turtle\n|Madagascar sea-eagle|sea ooze\n|olive ridley sea turtle\n|olive sea snake\n|red-backed sea eagle\n|rock sea lavender|sea celery\n|sea acorn|in a sea-way|sea asparagus|sea belt|sea burdock|sea crayfish|sea mink|sea whip|sea-bun|sea-fire|sea-magpie|sea-ox|sea-plant|sea-poacher|sea-rose|sea-whipcord\n|[[sea adder]] ({{taxlink|Syngnathus acus|species}})\n|[[sea anemone]] ({{taxfmt|Actiniaria|order}})\n|sea angel\n|sea ape\n|sea apple\n|sea arrow\n|sea bass\n|[[sea-bat]], [[sea bat]], [[seabat]]\n|sea bean\n|sea bear\n|seabeard\n|sea beaver\n|sea